  "stage": {
    "id": "bitcoin_advanced",
    "stageNumber": 2,
    "title": "Bitcoin Advanced Concepts",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "bitcoin_spv",
        "title": "SPV and Merkle Tree",
        "content": "## Verification Without a Full Node\n\nDoes every Bitcoin user need to store the entire blockchain (600GB+ as of 2026)? Satoshi proposed a solution for this too.\n\n### Simplified Payment Verification (SPV)\n\n> \"It is possible to verify payments without running a full network node.\"\n\n**How SPV Works**:\n1. Store only block headers (not full blocks)\n2. Verify specific transaction inclusion in a block via Merkle proof\n3. Maintain headers of the longest chain\n\n### Merkle Tree Structure\n\nA Merkle Tree stacks transaction hashes in a binary tree:\n\n```\n              Merkle Root\n              /        \\\n           H(AB)        H(CD)\n           /   \\        /   \\\n         H(A)  H(B)   H(C)  H(D)\n          |     |      |     |\n         TxA   TxB    TxC   TxD\n```\n\n**Verification Method**: To confirm TxB is in a block?\n- Only need H(A), H(CD), and Merkle Root\n- Calculate H(B), combine with H(A) to get H(AB)\n- Combine H(AB) and H(CD), compare with Merkle Root\n\n### Satoshi's Prediction vs Reality\n\n**2008 Whitepaper Prediction**:\n> \"Block headers: 80 bytes × 6 per hour × 24 × 365 = 4.2MB/year\"\n\n**2026 Reality**:\n- Bitcoin full node: **600GB+**\n- Block size: 1MB (with SegWit ~4MB)\n- SPV wallets still valid but privacy concerns exist\n\n### Analogy: Library Search\n\nTo check if a specific book exists in a huge library:\n- **Full Node**: Check every book directly (takes long time)\n- **SPV**: Use library catalog (Merkle Root) and a few hints (Merkle Path)\n\n### Limitations and Trade-offs\n\n- **Security**: Slightly lower than full node (must trust miners)\n- **Privacy**: SPV nodes may expose which addresses they're interested in\n- **BIP37 Bloom Filter**: Privacy improvement attempt, but still imperfect",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "bitcoin_state_transition",
        "title": "Bitcoin as State Transition System",
        "content": "## Seeing Bitcoin with New Eyes\n\nIn 2014, Vitalik Buterin reinterpreted Bitcoin from a new perspective in the Ethereum whitepaper:\n\n> \"Bitcoin is technically a state transition system.\"\n\n### What is State?\n\nBitcoin's 'state' = **ownership status of all unspent transaction outputs (UTXO)**\n\n| Concept | Description |\n|---------|-------------|\n| UTXO | Unspent Transaction Output — bitcoin not yet spent |\n| State | Who owns which UTXO at current point in time |\n\n### State Transition Function\n\n```\nAPPLY(S, TX) → S' or ERROR\n```\n\n- **S**: Current state (UTXO set)\n- **TX**: Transaction\n- **S'**: New state (UTXO set changed by TX)\n- **ERROR**: Invalid TX\n\n### Example\n\n```\nCurrent State S:\n  - Alice: 10 BTC (UTXO_A)\n  - Bob: 5 BTC (UTXO_B)\n\nTransaction TX: \"Alice sends 3 BTC to Bob\"\n\nAPPLY(S, TX):\n  1. Verify UTXO_A (owned by Alice, 10 BTC ✓)\n  2. Consume UTXO_A\n  3. Create new UTXOs:\n     - Bob: 3 BTC (new UTXO)\n     - Alice: 7 BTC (change UTXO)\n\nNew State S':\n  - Alice: 7 BTC (UTXO_A')\n  - Bob: 5 BTC (UTXO_B) + 3 BTC (UTXO_new)\n```\n\n### Why This Perspective Matters\n\nThis reinterpretation is the backdrop for Ethereum's creation:\n- Bitcoin: Limited state transitions (money transfers only)\n- Ethereum: **Generalized state transitions** (arbitrary computation possible)\n\n### Analogy: Chess Game\n\n- **State**: Current chess board arrangement\n- **Transaction**: One move\n- **State Transition Function**: Verify if move follows rules, generate new arrangement\n\nBitcoin is a simple game with limited rules for 'exchanging money'. Ethereum is a board game platform where you can **program any rules**.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "bitcoin_script_limits",
        "title": "Limitations of Bitcoin Script",
        "content": "## Why Can't Bitcoin Do 'Smart Contracts'?\n\nBitcoin has a simple programming language called **Script**. But Vitalik identified 4 key limitations.\n\n### 1. Lack of Turing-completeness\n\nBitcoin Script has **no loops**.\n\n```\n✓ IF-ELSE possible\n✗ WHILE, FOR loops impossible\n```\n\nReason? To prevent infinite loops. But the cost is significant — complex logic cannot be implemented.\n\n### 2. Value-blindness\n\n> \"UTXO is all-or-nothing.\"\n\n- **Impossible**: \"This script allows maximum 100 BTC withdrawal\"\n- UTXO scripts cannot **fine-control withdrawal amounts**\n- Hedging contracts, partial withdrawals difficult to implement\n\n### 3. Lack of state\n\n> \"UTXO exists only as spent or unspent.\"\n\n- **Only 2 states**: Used / Unused\n- Multi-stage contracts impossible (e.g., \"Stage 2 of 3 in progress\")\n- Escrow, subscription services, complex state management impossible\n\n### 4. Blockchain-blindness\n\nScript **cannot access**:\n- nonce (something like a random number)\n- timestamp\n- previous block hash\n\nResult: Gambling apps, time-based contracts impossible.\n\n### Ethereum's Answer\n\nThese 4 limitations are exactly why Ethereum was born:\n\n| Bitcoin Limitation | Ethereum Solution |\n|-------------------|-------------------|\n| No loops | Turing-complete EVM + Gas limit |\n| Value-blind | Direct account balance query/control |\n| No state | Contract storage (persistent) |\n| Blockchain-blind | block.timestamp, blockhash access |\n\n### Analogy: Calculator vs Computer\n\nBitcoin Script = **Pocket Calculator** (only addition, subtraction)\nEthereum Solidity = **General Purpose Computer** (program anything)\n\nCalculators are useful, but you need a computer to build complex apps.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
